The Bolsheviks are back in power.
Moscow—many years ago, during my sabbatical from teaching at an American university, I returned to my hometown Moscow.
It wasn't a sanctuary of free speech.
But there were still remnants of freedom here once.
Opposition leader Alexei Navalny once toured the country to seek support from politicians not controlled by the Kremlin.
Protests erupted among the public.
Independent non-governmental organizations operate domestically.
Journalists and analysts may not necessarily follow the Kremlin's line.
It was widely viewed as a legacy product of the past.
Protests erupted among the public after that, while opposition leader Alexei Navalny was imprisoned, and the protests he initiated were suppressed.
Its anti-corruption foundation was shut down for "extremism" and its members are either being exiled or investigated.
Almost every day, journalists, media outlets, human rights advocates, or independent institutions are being added to the list of "foreign agents" – and even worse – being labeled as "undesirables".
Although Russia has not slipped far from a non-free state in the past year, the slide has been quite steep.
For example, a 2012 law designated foreign agents, aimed at discrediting or undermining institutions or individuals engaging in "political activities" and receiving funding from abroad.
But the law's application has become increasingly arbitrary, to the point where sharing tweets is now a reason to be labeled a foreign agent.
The "undesirables" label will get you completely shut down.
This year alone, a record 101 entities have been added to the list of foreign agents.
Among the total of 359, 88 are media-related institutions and individuals.
According to Russia's government, the aforementioned "agents" must be listed because they "influence national politics."
But the core target of news and propaganda work, of course, is to influence politics.
While President Vladimir Putin has positioned himself to continue controlling Russian politics in the foreseeable future, he views criticism as a survival threat.
Despite having endured all this silence and persecution, it is the Communist Party, an unlikely group, that has managed to survive and become the only genuine opposition to the Kremlin.
This is largely due to Navalny's "smart voting" strategy, which involves encouraging people to support candidates most likely to defeat those backed by the Kremlin, while the Communist Party performed strongly in last month's parliamentary and regional elections.
Official data shows that Communist Party candidates won 18.9% of the State Duma (parliamentary) vote, while the United Russia Party, backed by the Kremlin, secured nearly 49.8%.
But the Communist Party refuses to acknowledge this outcome, insisting that the vote was manipulated.
In fact, some experts estimate that they should have won about 30% of the vote, while the United Russia Party should have secured around 35%.
For many Russians, the Communist Party seems to be more respected now than Putin.
But they are no longer the original Communist Party.
They not only do not deny the pleasures of the world, but party members are even fond of wearing fur coats, enthusiastic about traveling abroad, driving foreign cars, and using social media.
Some people are multimillionaires – for instance, Pavel Grudinin, the charismatic head of the agricultural ministry, who was barred from running in last month's election.
Although the party is still led by 77-year-old Gennady Zyuganov, it is increasingly influenced and supported by young party members.
For instance, Nikita Bondarenko.
Nicknamed the "red Navalny," 36-year-old Nikita Bondarenko severely criticized the poorly designed pension reform of 2018.
Recently, when a regional minister suggested that Russians should be able to live better on their meager monthly salary of 3,500 rubles (approximately $50), Bondarenko recorded his efforts to prove this person wrong on his YouTube channel.
Despite being threatened with disqualification, Nikita Bondarenko was still allowed to participate in the State Duma elections held last month.
Although he received support from Navalny's smart voting system, he still lost to the United Russia Party's candidate.
However, his potential should not be overlooked: he recently came up with a title for a protest, accusing "the state and the government" of taking over the United Russia.
Thereafter, there was 43-year-old Anastasiya Udodsova.
Like Bondarenko, she incredibly lost the last election.
However, she still remains very — and increasingly — popular.
Thanks to Navalny's smart voting system, another rising star, elegant Yekaterina Engalycheva, was elected to the Moscow City Duma in 2019.
It's particularly ironic that the Communist Party's modernization reflects a yearning for the past: in 1917, Lenin's Bolsheviks promised justice and equality, and while the state that implemented those ideals was strict, it was still not devoid of justice and compassion.
Like Navalny, the modern Communist Party today represents a predictable and consistent vision, under which one person's fanciful ideas won't affect everyone.
It is precisely based on this logic that all the Kremlin's opponents are increasingly joining forces: forming the "United Russia" that can counter Putin under the United Russia Party.
This situation is not unique to Russia.
In the recent parliamentary elections in the Czech Republic, Andrej Babiš, also known as the Czech Donald Trump, failed to be re-elected as prime minister, as the opposition alliance put aside their ideological differences to form a united coalition, with its leader Petr Fiala likely to lead a new government alongside another opposition alliance.
As Fiala said, "People have had enough of populists," they want "normal, competent, and decent politics."
Hungary's opposition is also planning to field a united election list in next year's parliamentary elections and put forward a single candidate to run for prime minister.
Of course, the Czech Republic still maintains a democratic system, so Babiš is preparing to join the opposition forces.
Overturning Putin, however, would be a much greater challenge, and it's not hard to anticipate that even more sweeping measures aimed at crushing the Communist Party will follow.
But these actions have also posed a risk to the Kremlin.
Now the situation is that the president claims that Russian democracy "has not died out," and points to the existence of "vibrant opposition" as evidence, which suggests that he is at least still interested in pretending that Russia is not being steered towards nearly authoritarianism.
Putin claims he only wants stability.
But its regime is pushing Russia into even more turbulent circumstances.
If the Kremlin were to treat Russian liberals with the same capriciousness in making and enforcing rules, driving the Communist Party underground, a social explosion would be even more likely to occur.
If it were to decide not to suppress them anymore, the Russian Communists – yes, the Communists – could become a force that cannot be ignored.
